<br>
The example of land-based turbines here in the US is illustrative.<br>
<br>
A 1.5 megawatt turbine is placed one per every five acres, on an 1/8 acre pad. Farming and grazing are in no way impacted - except that soil erosion is somewhat lessened.<br>
<br>
From the farmeres perspective, they receive about 100 dollars per acre of grain and a leasing fee of 2,000 dollars per wind turbine. It is wind turbines that are helping to save farming.<br>
<br>
It is completely erroneous to use the gross land area that a wind-farm occupies - on or off shore to determine impacts.<br>
<br>
BTW - a typical nuclear plant requires 400 miles of transmission lines carried on 1,800 towers (more than the numer of turbines required to produce the same power) - a MUCH more severe impact to land.<br>
<br>
