<br>
You are thinking like an American (Not unreasonable, under the circumstances) The UK, particularly southern England, is one of the most densely populated countries in the world. Even our open countryside is probably as densely populated as some US city Suburbs.<br>
<br>
As I said, I am not opposed to wind farms in principle. In countries like the USA with literally millions of square miles of virtually uninhabited land there is not a problem. And indeed wind farms may well be the best way of providing power for the more remote rural areas (as it has been for over a century!) But it is not like that in the UK.<br>
<br>
The point of the “Double use” is well taken and is a valid point for the USA. However in the UK most of the countryside is already in double use. Farming and housing! While wind farms may be compatible with agriculture they are not compatible with housing.<br>
<br>
Anecdotal evidence (poor TV signals and broken mobile ‘phone connections when even helicopters fly overhead) suggests that anybody living in the vicinity of a land based wind farm would experience severe disruption to radio, TV and telecommunications. Quite apart from the visual impact and noise! <br>
<br>
The bit about the 400 miles of transmission lines also doesn’t apply in the UK. We tend to generate electricity nearer to where it is used (we aren’t big enough to do it any other way!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ) Any new nuclear stations would be built around the coast. Most of the UK is within 60 miles of the coast (I think the furthest you can be from the sea is about 97 miles)<br>
<br>
Elsewhere recently comparisons have been made between Britain and Sweden suggesting that Sweden is oh-so-green with their high percentage of renewables and we in the UK are absolute rotters for only managing 1%<br>
<br>
It is worth considering that Sweden has a population a tad bigger than that of London in a land area nearly twice that of the entire UK This gives them a Population density of around 50/square mile as compared with the UK population density of more like 650/square mile.<br>
<br>
Sweden is basically deserted by UK standards, as is the USA! Its even worse if you consider England on her own, Scotland and Wales have only small populations but between them account for a good proportion of the overall land area. England must be well over 1000/square mile. If Sweden couldn’t manage a good portion of renewables they should, rightly, be ashamed of themselves. In fact, with Sweden’s resources I am surprised they went for Nuclear power in the first place. They don’t really need it. The UK (and particularly England) is in a somewhat different position. Most renewable technologies are land hungry  (Not necessarily in a destructive way, though hydro has its opponents) In the UK we simply don’t have the land to indulge in Gigawatts worth of windmills and in any case there wouldn’t be much point anyway. <br>
<br>
Britain is a high population density country and will need high energy density solutions (IYSWIM)<br>
<br>
Britain also has a problem. We don’t mine much coal any more and our oil and gas will be more or less gone in the next 30 years.<br>
<br>
Whenever anybody talks about renewables they always talk about electricity. This completely misses the point. Two thirds of our energy requirements (or more) go on transport and space heating. Currently electricity is only a small part of it. Over 90% of our energy inputs are fossil derived<br>
<br>
In order to replace our current fossil input we (In the UK) would need between 200 and 300 Gw of alternative power. Even at the extreme I doubt if renewables could provide more than 10% of that and to do this would require our entire landscape, coastline etc being converted into industrial installations, something that I really wouldn’t want to see, and, In any case, we would still have to find the other 90% from somewhere else.<br>
<br>
In order to replace our current fossil input; we (In the UK) would need to build around 200 nuclear reactors!<br>
<br>
It takes a lot of resources to engage in a construction programme on this scale. If we wait until we need to do it we probably wont be able to do it, we need to start now while we are still comfortable and everything seems fine.<br>
<br>
If we don’t do this we are going to be in Deep-@#%$ by 2050! I am old enough to remember what an energy famine feels like (The 3 day week) however unlike past energy famines the one that will hit us (if we don’t take action now) by mid century wont go away!<br>
<br>
